<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-payroll-failed-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Payroll failed,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A failed payroll run is one that didn&rsquo;t process the way it should: the run wouldn&rsquo;t submit, the direct deposit didn&rsquo;t fund, one or more employees weren&rsquo;t paid, or the run errored out partway through. People say payroll &ldquo;failed&rdquo; or &ldquo;didn&rsquo;t go through,&rdquo; and underneath that phrase is usually one of a handful of causes &mdash; most often not enough money in the funding account when the direct deposit drafted, or the direct-deposit lead time and cutoff being missed.</p>
      <p>The honest part is the split. Whether the <em>payroll service itself</em> processed &mdash; the subscription, the e-services / direct-deposit activation, and the movement of money &mdash; lives in your Intuit account and is Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve. What an independent ProAdvisor fixes is the <em>setup and the books</em>: making sure the company and employee bank details are right, the employee setup is complete, the run is recorded correctly, and the payroll liabilities reconcile. The fix steps below confirm funding and timing first, then verify the Intuit-side service, then correct the setup &mdash; and finally reconcile what did and didn&rsquo;t post so the records are clean.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

